activity.p:
Here is an example of solving the equation 3x + 4 = 16 using a complete presentation:

    \begin{aligned}
        3x + 4 \amp = 16 \\
        3x \amp = 12 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Subtract $4$ from both sides} \\
        x \amp = 4 \amp \amp \text{Divide both sides by $3$}
    \end{aligned}

p.me:
\begin{aligned}
    5x - 7 \amp = 23 \\
    5x \amp = 30 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Add $7$ to both sides} \\
    x \amp = 6 \amp \amp \text{Divide both sides by $5$}
\end{aligned}

\begin{aligned}
    5x + 9 \amp = -3x - 7 \\
    5x \amp = -3x - 16 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Subtract $9$ from both sides} \\
    8x \amp = -16 \amp \amp \text{Add $3x$ to both sides} \\
    x \amp = -2 \amp \amp \text{Divide both sides by $8$}
\end{aligned}

activity.p:
            There is a common way of writing equations that some people use which is less than ideal:
            
                
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (-0.7, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 4x$};
                        \draw (-0.3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut +$};
                        \draw (-0.0, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 7$};
                        \draw (0.25, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut =$};
                        \draw (0.75, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 19$};

                        \draw (-0.21, -0.4) node[anchor=center] {$\strut -7$};
                        \draw (0.7, -0.4) node[anchor=center] {$\strut -7$};

                        \draw (-1, -0.6) -- (1, -0.6);

                        \draw (-0.7, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 4x$};
                        \draw (0.25, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut =$};
                        \draw (0.75, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 12$};

                        \draw (-0.9, -1.05) -- (-0.5, -1.05);
                        \draw (-0.7, -1.05) node[anchor=north] {$4$};
                        \draw (0.6, -1.05) -- (0.95, -1.05);
                        \draw (0.775, -1.05) node[anchor=north] {$4$};
                        
                        \draw (0.3,-1.7) node[anchor=center] {$x=3$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}

            There are a number of problems with this. To start, there's not really an organized way to read this. The
            best way to think of it is that it breaks apart into four pieces with three of them overlapping each other.
            Another problem is that the reader is expected to simply know what's happening. This is sometimes at the
            root of students' complaints about "skipped steps." 
            
                
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{scope}[shift={(-6,0)}]
                            \draw (0,0.3) node[anchor=south] {\strut Original Problem};
                        
                            \draw (-0.7, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 4x$};
                            \draw (-0.3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut +$};
                            \draw (-0.0, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 7$};
                            \draw (0.25, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut =$};
                            \draw (0.75, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 19$};
                        \end{scope}

                        \begin{scope}[shift={(-2,0)}]
                            \draw (0,0.8) node[anchor=south] {\strut Subtract 7 to};
                            \draw (0,0.3) node[anchor=south] {\strut get a new equation};

                            \draw (-0.7, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 4x$};
                            \draw (-0.3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut +$};
                            \draw (-0.0, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 7$};
                            \draw (0.25, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut =$};
                            \draw (0.75, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 19$};
                        
                            \draw (-0.21, -0.4) node[anchor=center] {$\strut -7$};
                            \draw (0.7, -0.4) node[anchor=center] {$\strut -7$};
                        
                            \draw (-1, -0.6) -- (1, -0.6);
                        
                            \draw (-0.7, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 4x$};
                            \draw (0.25, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut =$};
                            \draw (0.75, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 12$};
                        \end{scope}
                        
                        \begin{scope}[shift={(2,0)}]
                            \draw (0,0.8) node[anchor=south] {\strut Divide the new};
                            \draw (0,0.3) node[anchor=south] {\strut equation by 4};

                            \draw (-0.7, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 4x$};
                            \draw (0.25, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut =$};
                            \draw (0.75, -0.85) node[anchor=center] {$\strut 12$};

                            \draw (-0.9, -1.05) -- (-0.5, -1.05);
                            \draw (-0.7, -1.05) node[anchor=north] {$4$};
                            \draw (0.6, -1.05) -- (0.95, -1.05);
                            \draw (0.775, -1.05) node[anchor=north] {$4$};
                        \end{scope}
                        
                        \begin{scope}[shift={(5.5,0)}]
                            \draw (0,0.3) node[anchor=south] {\strut Final answer};
                            \draw (0.3,-1.7) node[anchor=center] {$x=3$};
                        \end{scope}
                    \end{tikzpicture}

p.me:
\begin{aligned}
    4x + 7 \amp = 19 \\
    4x \amp = 12 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Subtract $7$ from both sides} \\
    x \amp = 3 \amp \amp \text{Divide both sides by $4$}
\end{aligned}

activity.p:
The act of explicitly stating what mathematical operation you're performing helps your brain to make
categories of information. A more simple "error" of this type is that some students refer to all algebraic
manipulations as "moving the term to the other side." Here are two examples of what that could mean to
students:

    
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw (-3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\begin{aligned}
                3x + 5 \amp = 14 \\
                3x \amp = 9
            \end{aligned}$};
            \draw (3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\begin{aligned}
                3x - 7 \amp = 14 \\
                3x \amp = 21
            \end{aligned}$};
        \end{tikzpicture}

Each of these is a different mathematical operation and a different algebraic step. It is not uncommon to
see the following mistakes:

    
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw (-3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\begin{aligned}
                3x + 5 \amp = 14 \\
                3x \amp \overset{\times}{=} 19
            \end{aligned}$};
            \draw (3, 0) node[anchor=center] {$\begin{aligned}
                3x - 7 \amp = 14 \\
                3x \amp \overset{\times}{=} 7
            \end{aligned}$};
        \end{tikzpicture}

p.me:
\begin{aligned}
    3x + 5 \amp = 14 \\
    3x \amp = 9 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Subtract $5$ from both sides} \\
    x \amp = 3 \amp \amp \text{Divide both sides by $3$}
\end{aligned}

\begin{aligned}
    3x - 7 \amp = 14 \\
    3x \amp = 21 \amp \eqnspacer \amp \text{Add $7$ to both sides} \\
    x \amp = 7 \amp \amp \text{Divide both sides by $3$}
\end{aligned}
